tspan.tspan: Fantastic containers and how to tame them

flowRoot.flowPara: Contemporary neuroimaging research is computationally intensive and heavily relies on analysis software. Results of an analysis might depend not only on the version of the software the scientist is using, but also on the overall computational environment (including the operating system, preinstalled software, environment variables, and data). Containerized computing environments, using Docker and Singularity , gained popularity as a means to maximize portability of complete environments, minimize operational variance across available infrastructure (laptops/HPC/cloud), and share complete environments. While containers are a very powerful technology, additional care and tooling are necessary to use them efficiently and reproducibly. We explore containers-oriented computing across the container life cycle—creation, validation (QA), storage (dissemination), and usage—along with approaches and tooling to assist at each step. This overview will focus on the reproducibility aspects, including the reproducibility of the containers themselves, and highlight recent technological developments.

flowPara.flowSpan: The technologies listed in the poster are open source software

flowRoot.flowPara: Containers assist with sharing complete analysis pipelines, facilitating efficient use of computing infrastructure without sacrificing reproducibility. But they are not a panacea for the reproducibility problem by themselves.
The tools presented here can assist in addressing these problems, helping to ensure the availability and reproducibility of containers in the long run.
• solution for software sustainability or integration
• are portable and can be used on most operating systems
• provide easy access to broad range of existing environments from container hubs
• can be used for “quick&dirty” bundling of computing elements
• are isolated and easy to install/remove
• could be kept under the same version control system as for code and data (DataLad)
• facilitate the introduction of a unified interface to a wide range of separate environments (e.g. BIDS apps, Boutiques, Gears)
• run only GNU/Linux, and Singularity can be ran only on GNU/Linux
• might leak host environment into containers
• might be incompatible with the elderly host system
• typically there are no easy ways to figure out what and how was installed into a container
• and what licenses cover the pieces, etc (see e.g. https://lwn.net/Articles/786066/)
• Hard-to-impossible to inspect/compare different containers on how they differ
• solution for software sustainability or integration
